<div3 type="article" n="1" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head>Married,</head> 
<div4 type="wed" n="1" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head /> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="303" /> <placeName key="tgn,7013964" n="1.000 1" reg="richmond, richmond, virginia" authname="tgn,7013964">In Richmond</placeName>, <dateStruct value="-03-16" full="yes" authname="--03-16"><month reg="03" full="yes">March</month> <day reg="16" full="yes">16th</day></dateStruct>, at <orgName n="St.James Church" type="church">St. James's Church</orgName>, by <persName n="Peterkin,Reverend,,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00095" reg="mostcommon:Peterkin,nomatch:0" authname="peterkin"><roleName n="Reverend" full="yes">the Rev. Dr.</roleName> <surname full="yes">Peterkin</surname></persName>, <persName n="Robinson,,Edward,T.,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00096" reg="default:Robinson,Edward,T.,," authname="robinson,edward,t."><foreName full="yes">Edward</foreName> <foreName full="yes">T.</foreName> <surname full="yes">Robinson</surname></persName> and <persName><foreName full="yes">Nannie</foreName></persName> M., daughter of <persName n="Robinson,,William,M.,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00097" reg="default:Robinson,William,M.,," authname="robinson,william,m."><foreName full="yes">William</foreName> <foreName full="yes">M.</foreName> <surname full="yes">Robinson</surname></persName>, <rs type="role">Esq.</rs>, formerly of <placeName reg="Petersburg, Petersburg, Virginia" key="tgn,7014404" authname="tgn,7014404">Petersburg</placeName>. </p> </div4> 
<div4 type="wed" n="2" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head /> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="304" /> On <dateStruct value="-03-2" full="yes" authname="--03-02"><day type="name" full="yes">Thursday</day>, <month reg="03" full="yes">March</month> <day reg="2" full="yes">2d</day></dateStruct>, at <placeName reg="St. Peter's Cathedral">St. Peter's Cathedral</placeName>, by <persName n="McGill,Right-Reverend,Bishop,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00098" reg="default:McGill,Bishop,,," authname="mcgill,bishop"><roleName n="Right-Reverend" full="yes">the Right Rev.</roleName> <foreName full="yes">Bishop</foreName> <surname full="yes">McGill</surname></persName>, <persName n="Govers,Captain,John,C.,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00099" reg="default:Govers,John,C.,," authname="govers,john,c."><roleName n="Captain" full="yes">Captain</roleName> <foreName full="yes">John</foreName> <foreName full="yes">C.</foreName> <surname full="yes">Govers</surname></persName>, <orgName type="regiment" key="15VARegiment">Fifteenth Virginia regiment</orgName>, to <persName n="Carr,Miss,Annie,G.,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00100" reg="default:Carr,Annie,G.,," authname="carr,annie,g."><roleName n="Miss" full="yes">Miss</roleName> <foreName full="yes">Annie</foreName> <foreName full="yes">G.</foreName> <surname full="yes">Carr</surname></persName>, of <placeName key="tgn,7013964" n="1.000 4" reg="richmond, richmond, virginia" authname="tgn,7013964">Richmond</placeName>. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="305" /> <orgName n="New York Herald" type="newspaper">New York Herald</orgName> and Sun please copy. * </p> </div4> </div3> 
<div3 type="death" n="2" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head /> 
<div4 type="obit" n="1" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head>Obituary.</head> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="306" /> Departed this life on the <dateStruct value="1865-03-20" full="yes" authname="1865-03-20"><day reg="20" full="yes">20th</day> day of <month reg="03" full="yes">March</month>, <year full="yes">1865</year>,</dateStruct> <persName n="Valentine,,Mann,S.,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00101" reg="default:Valentine,Mann,S.,," authname="valentine,mann,s."><foreName full="yes">Mann</foreName> <foreName full="yes">S.</foreName> <surname full="yes">Valentine</surname></persName>, in the <num value="79" type="ordinal">seventy-ninth</num> year of his age. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="307" /> Not. to conform to custom, not with a wish to attract attention to him now passed from earth forever, has this brief notice of his life and death been drawn amidst the lingering agonies of that separation.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="308" />But a son, a husband, a father, a master, a friend, such as he was, "liveth not to himself, neither death he to himself." We know from whence comes every attribute of soul that so endears man to his fellow; and while we thus present to the world for its contemplation those attributes, are we not but inviting men to a view of their divine source!

<milestone unit="sentence" n="309" />He who has just left this earth — well did he know how to look from nature up to nature's <name n="God" type="God">God</name>; and all things that were sublime or beautiful in man or in the world around him were to him ever incentives to the heart's holiest worship.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="310" />This was the habit of his though. "<name n="God" type="God">God's</name> noblest work, an honest man," whatever might have been his grade in life, was ever with him an object of peculiar interest; and who can doubt but <sic>that that </sic> interest, thus shown, has strengthened many a heart in its pursuit of the true and the right, and that <name n="God" type="God">God's</name> kingdom, by this feeble means, has been hastened to its coming?

<milestone unit="sentence" n="311" />But not in man alone did he seek for the manifestations of his Creator.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="312" />To him nature had a voice so sweet, so tender, so touching, that it seemed an angel's voice sent from earth to Heaven to sing of <name n="God" type="God">God's</name> mercy and benevolence to men. Hush, heart, thy anguish!

<milestone unit="sentence" n="313" />It must be told.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="314" />The <num value="1">one</num> who writes these lines, in childhood's earliest hour was taught by him to look upon the stars, the changing seasons, the tiny insect, the gathering cloud, the bursting storm, and mark, with awe and adoration, the workings of the great Invisible.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="315" />Often has this <num value="1">one</num> watched, with a silent, unuttered prayer of thanks to heaven, the softening light steal ever his face as he dwelt with a warm admiration upon the all-wise, the all-mysterious workings of a loving Father in His creation.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="316" />On <num value="1">one</num> occasion, after walking alone on the porch for a long while, he suddenly came in said, with tears in his eyes, "There is a dear little bird building us nest in the old catalpa tree: see that no <num value="1">one</num> disturbs it."--Mingling through a long life in the busy world never took from him the beautiful freshness of childhood, or the stern integrity of principle, strengthened by manhood.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="317" />His true character not many knew.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="318" />With a pride which seemed almost inconsistent with such softer emotions, he endeavored to conceal the more sacred feelings of his soul, and often preferred being misunderstood rather than reveal them in their great depths.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="319" />They who knew him best have never rounded those depths; but they yet look with longing eyes to that eternity which, while revealing the mighty emotions of the human heart, shall present to their view that fountain whose waters alone gave them life as it flowed out from the great bosom of Him who has called himself-Love.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="320" />Until that hour, dear, earthly father, thy weeping ones will call to mind thy precepts, and feeling that a hand divine has laid this heavy burden on their hearts, will say to thy spirit, raintstering bound them. "Take to <name n="God" type="God">God</name> thy dear <num value="1">one</num>'s message, 'we submit.'" </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="321" /> For long, long years, the deceased believed that <name n="God" type="God">God</name> was revealed to man sufficiently in nature; although, during that period, he was a reader, almost a student, of the <name>Bibre</name>.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="322" />Reverently, and with unfeigned admiration, had he ever spoken of its precepts; and religion — that religion which comes to man by nature; or, may it not be more properly said by the <unclear /> of <name n="God" type="God">God's</name> own spirit,--found in him never a <unclear> </unclear> or a doubter.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="323" />He believed sincerely in its reality, and those who gave him unmistakable evidences of their sincerity as Christians had over him an influence which he himself did not knew they possessed.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="324" />This influence was <num value="1">one</num> of the means which <name n="God" type="God">God</name> was then using to bring him into the light of that more perfect revelation of Himself which was eventually to crown his earnest, heartfelt search for the <name>Great Infinite</name>.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="325" />Troubles--<name n="God" type="God">God's</name> blessings misinterpreted — came heavily.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="326" />They fell upon the heart of the deceased.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="327" />He mourned over the sorrows he could not alleviate.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="328" />When the devoted defenders of this country passed, with a weary step, to new a cross of duty, he would bury his face in his hands, weep like a child, and retire into the solitude of his own room.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="329" />The world had seemed to have lost all of comfort for him. He withdrew from society, and gave himself up to hours of thought and of reading.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="330" />How sad to see him thus forget, in his sorrows for others, that his own failing spirits were hastening him on to death.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="331" />Those were the <num value="1000">thousand</num> of his friends.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="332" />Ah. how short- sighted is man — It was <name n="God" type="God">God</name> who thus led him from companionship with man to a secret communion with Himself.--He was alone with his Creator, who was then deepening, intensifying and enlightening his soul with that presence whose glory had, for so many long years, been seen afar off, and so dimly.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="333" />Carefully were works on religion read, and with a deep interest and pleasure, excited by a desire to grasp that vague undefined something for which the soul knew no name, and without which it could no longer rest.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="334" />His Bible — there it lies, chosen passages so lately marked by his own trembling hand:"I am the <name>Word</name>, and the <name>Word</name> was God" Thoughts almost too sacred to be dwelt upon: the communion between man and his <name n="God" type="God">God</name>.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="335" />Did that merciful Father leave his work unfinished!

<milestone unit="sentence" n="336" />Conviction says not. A few hours before his departure, the faithful minister of <persName n="Christ,,,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00102" reg="mostcommon:Christ,nomatch:0" authname="christ"><surname full="yes">Christ</surname></persName> knelt at his bed, and prayed that the passing soul might receive that blessing which comes through <persName n="Christ,,,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00103" reg="mostcommon:Christ,nomatch:0" authname="christ"><surname full="yes">Christ</surname></persName> alone.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="337" />This prayer of faith went up to <name n="God" type="God">God</name>, and the holy calm and peace that entered the soul of his servant mirrored itself in beauty on his countenance, and <name n="God" type="God">God's</name> holy angels must have rejoiced that he who, in darkness, had groped so persistently to come into the light, had seen that Light come down to him in all the unsullied purity and beauty of the day of Heaven.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="338" />Never by that family of kindred and servants, who so mouth his lose, can those solemn hours be forgotten — those hours when Christians, boldly claiming their privileges before their High Priest, called on Heaven importunate for a hearing — Heaven could not deny them, for her promise had gone forth.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="339" />Prayer, with Faith's petition damp with the tears of earth, ascended up on high, and the passly gates flew open, whence a shining throng poured forth and bore from earth a soul forever saved.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="340" /><name n="God" type="God">God</name>, by His infinite power, grant that this His mercy may not be lost upon any; but that, kindling in the bosoms of all the fires of love and gratitude, they may make and pay unto Him vows whose effects can never be lost through eternity. *] B. </p> </div4> 
<div4 type="obit" n="2" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head /> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="341" /> Died, on the <dateStruct value="-02-27" full="yes" authname="--02-27"><day reg="27" full="yes">27th</day> of <month reg="02" full="yes">February</month></dateStruct> last, of rheumatism of the heart, <persName n="Chappell,,Bettie,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00104" reg="default:Chappell,Bettie,,," authname="chappell,bettie"><foreName full="yes">Bettie</foreName> <surname full="yes">Chappell</surname></persName>, daughter of <persName><foreName full="yes">Robert</foreName></persName> B and <persName n="Harris,,Martha,F.,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00105" reg="default:Harris,Martha,F.,," authname="harris,martha,f."><foreName full="yes">Martha</foreName> <foreName full="yes">F.</foreName> <surname full="yes">Harris</surname></persName>, aged <measure n="14years" type="date">fourteen years</measure> and <measure n="3months" type="date">three months</measure>. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="342" /> When the old and weary ones of earth he down and die, and when we commit their lifeless remains to the dark and lonely <unclear /> we perform the last sad rites with a feeling of resignation to the <name>Divine</name> will, for we know that the sear and yellow leaves of autumn must fall, that flowers must fade and decay in their appointed time, and that all of animate and inanimate nature is born to died.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="343" />But it is a sad reflection, that while "the old <hi rend="italics">must <unclear>dor,</unclear></hi> the young <hi rend="italics">may</hi> " The green leaves of the forest are scattered by the <unclear>tornado</unclear> and the whirlwind; the beautiful flowers of spring are plucked from their parent stems to fade, wither and die; and thus the icy hand of Death is after laid upon sweet and innocent children, and we seem to hear death say: </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="344" /> <cit><q direct="unspecified"> <lg type="stanza" org="uniform" sample="complete"> <l>For me must the father his loved child resign, </l><l>And mother, and babe at the breast, must be mine.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="345" /></l><l>The brother and sister for me are to part, </l><l>And loved ones to break off each tie of the heart.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="346" /></l> </lg> </q><bibl default="NO" /></cit> </p> 
<p> And so in our sweet <persName><foreName full="yes">Bettie</foreName></persName>'s death — the father has resigned his child, the mother has given up her babe, the brother and sister have parted, the tender ties of affection that we had woven around her little favorite have been rudely sundered; and though with humble resignation and submission to the chastening hand of <name n="God" type="God">God</name> we strive to bear our bereavement without complaining; still </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="347" /> <cit><q direct="unspecified"> <lg type="stanza" org="uniform" sample="complete"> <l>Our souls are sad, as if the woe </l><l>Of untold years were seated there, </l><l>And through their deepest channels flow </l><l>The bitter waters of despair!

<milestone unit="sentence" n="348" /></l><l>Our sun of life seems set in gloom; </l><l>A clutching grief affects each heart-- </l><l>We've laid our darling in the tomb; </l><l>Oh, misery, thus to part!

<milestone unit="sentence" n="349" /></l> </lg> </q><bibl default="NO" /></cit> </p> 
<p> We might here endeavor to draw a photograph of the sweet girl whom we mourn; but her various her amiability, her affectionate devotion, her kindness, charity, gentleness, and <name>Christian</name> fortitude under sufferings and afflictions, are all engraves upon the tablets of our memory, never, never to be effaced, and we know that she now dwells in a world where pain and anguish are no more.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="350" />Then, dear <persName><foreName full="yes">Bettie</foreName></persName>. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="351" /> Why should we weep for thee?

<milestone unit="sentence" n="352" />Why should we sigh. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="353" /> That thus early in life thy young spirit doth fly From earth and its turmoil to pleasures above, To vie with bright angels in anthems of love: </p> <closer> <signed>C. C. B.</signed> </closer> </div4> </div3> </div2> </div1> <milestone unit="page" n="3" /> 
